## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why This Breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006). The runtime no longer supports preemptive thread termination. You must use **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Pattern Classification

| Original Code | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `while (_running)` loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `IsCancellationRequested`, continue loop |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Force stop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `GetNextItem()` may block | Blocking call interruption | Pass token to blocking call |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work (replaces ThreadAbortException catch)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just continue to loop condition,
                // which will now exit because token is cancelled.
                // If you want to continue processing remaining items
                // (like ResetAbort did), break out selectively instead.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after timeout, the thread is truly stuck.
        // Unlike Thread.Abort, there's no force-kill — see pitfalls below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Adapting `GetNextItem` to Accept Cancellation

The original could block indefinitely. You **must** make it cancellation-aware:

```csharp
// If using a BlockingCollection<T>:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}

// If using a manual wait:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Replace: _signal.WaitOne();
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---|---|
| **Blocking call ignores token** | If `GetNextItem` doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, cancellation stalls until it returns. Every blocking method in the chain must forward the token. |
| **No force-kill equivalent** | There is no `Thread.Abort` replacement. If code is truly stuck (deadlock, unmanaged call), the only option is `Process.Kill` on a child process. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` doesn't check tokens** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` — returns immediately on cancellation. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers/callbacks. Always wrap in `IDisposable` or `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level loop. Let it propagate elsewhere. |
| **`ResetAbort` pattern** | The original caught the abort and continued looping. With cooperative cancellation, once cancelled, the token stays cancelled. If you need per-item cancellation (abort one item, continue the next), use a **linked token per work item** — see below. |

### Per-Item Cancellation (ResetAbort Equivalent)

If the original intent was "abort the current item but keep the loop running":

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken shutdownToken)
{
    while (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Per-item timeout or cancellation
        using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(shutdownToken);
        itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // optional timeout

        try
        {
            var item = GetNextItem(shutdownToken);
            ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Item was cancelled/timed out, but shutdown wasn't requested
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            continue; // keep processing — this is the ResetAbort equivalent
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break; // full shutdown requested
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

### Migration Checklist

- ✅ Replace `volatile bool` flag with `CancellationTokenSource`
- ✅ Replace `Thread.Abort()` with `cts.Cancel()`
- ✅ Replace `catch (ThreadAbortException)` with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`
- ✅ Remove `Thread.ResetAbort()` — use loop continuation or linked tokens
- ✅ Replace `Thread.Sleep(2000)` with `Thread.Join(timeout)` for shutdown
- ✅ Pass `CancellationToken` through to all blocking calls
- ✅ Implement `IDisposable` to clean up `CancellationTokenSource`
- ✅ No SYSLIB0006 warnings remain
